<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Sun Microsystems
   To Unveil Faster
   Computer `Server'
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/30/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   SUNW
</CO>
<MS>
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<NS>
NEW PRODUCTS &amp; SERVICES (PDT)
</NS>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. -- Sun Microsystems Inc., attempting
to fill a gaping hole in its product line, said it plans to
unveil today a new line of high-speed "multiprocessing"
servers, computers that use more than one processor.
   Sun is aiming its new line, the Sparcserver 600MP, at
users in big corporations, where servers are often used to
connect desktop computers into networks and central data
bases. The 600MP, with list prices ranging from $45,000 to
just over $105,000, will go up against machines from
formidable incumbents such as International Business Machines
Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sun has the world's biggest market share in the
workstation computers that are often used by engineers, but
it has lagged in the market for high-end servers that
businesses are increasingly using to replace old-line
mainframe and mini-computers. Sun's servers were seen as too
slow and lacked the sophisticated software needed to direct
the complex tasks that such machines are asked to do.
   "On the server side we've been pretty primitive," said
<PERSON>Lawrence Hambly</PERSON>, vice president of marketing of <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s
computer unit. "This is the first really major announcement
of servers that really are worth calling servers."
   The new servers come in versions with two and four central
processors, the "brains" of the machines, and run typical
business software at around 140 transactions per second, a
common measure of computing speed. That's nearly three times
as fast as <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s previous, similarly priced, server models,
<PERSON>Mr. Hambly</PERSON> said.
   Analysts said Sun's new servers are likely to be a hit
with existing Sun users, but they are more skeptical of <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s
ability to succeed outside its own camp. The machines "will
be a home run for Sun in its own native market but they're 18
months late," said <PERSON>Douglas Crook</PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION>Dataquest
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a market-research firm.
   Companies such as <ORGANIZATION>Solbourne Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Longmont</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Colo.</LOCATION>, have sold multiprocessing machines since <DATE>1989</DATE>. And
Sun, facing an increasingly crowded market for servers in
corporate computer rooms, isn't likely to make big headway in
business applications such as data base servers and online
transaction processing, <PERSON>Mr. Crook</PERSON> said. "They've got
competitors with faster boxes and better technology who've
been there longer," he said.
   Sun also will announce a multiprocessing version of its
Unix operating system, Sun's <PERSON>Mr. Hambly</PERSON> said. Sun will offer
devices allowing users of existing Sun server models to
convert their machines to multiprocessing machines while
keeping the older computers outer package and disk drives, he
said.
</TEXT>
