<HL>
   Technology:
   Sun Microsystems Inc. to Introduce Line
   To Bolster Lead in Low-Cost Work Units
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/22/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   DEC HWP IBM SGI SUNW
</CO>
<MS>
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
MASSACHUSETTS (MA)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
NEW YORK (NY)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. plans to unveil today a range of
speedier new computers that defend Sun's position as the
leader in low-cost workstations.
   Separately, Hewlett-Packard Co. says it has sped up its
own workstations. And Silicon Graphics Inc. plans to announce
today a low-cost "multimedia" computer that processes
high-quality music and video along with fast
three-dimensional graphics now available only in expensive
workstations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While Sun's new workstations are vital to maintain its
position as the highest-volume workstation vendor, analysts
said, the machines don't provide the high-performance machine
they feel Sun needs to compete with offerings from
<ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>H-P</ORGANIZATION>.
   "It's a ho-hum announcement," said <PERSON>Nancy Battey</PERSON>, a
research director at <ORGANIZATION>International Data Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, a
market-research firm. "It continues Sun's leadership in
low-cost. But what they're still lacking is leading-edge
computer performance."
   Sun officials said its new machines are "enhanced"
versions of existing products. One of the machines, the
<ORGANIZATION>Sparcstation ELC</ORGANIZATION>, listing for <MONEY>$4,995</MONEY>, is <PERCENT>50%</PERCENT> faster and has
four times the memory of its predecessor, the <MONEY>$6,995</MONEY>
Sparcstation IPC. Another, the <ORGANIZATION>Sparcstation IPX</ORGANIZATION>, will be
similar to the Sun's existing Sparcstation 2 but will list at
<MONEY>$11,995</MONEY>, or <PERCENT>25%</PERCENT> less than the older machine.
   With its low-cost workstations, Sun has aggressively gone
after the large pool of users who typically buy personal
computers for business and technical computing tasks. The
Mountain View, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, company's inexpensive machines have
helped it build its No. 1 share of the workstation market.
Sun plans to entice more low-end computer users through a
trade-in program, whereby users can get a <MONEY>$1,000</MONEY> discount on
its IPC color workstation by trading in competitors'
workstations or highend PCs.
   Sun is also a leader in introducing workstations that
employ reduced-instruction-set computing, or Risc, a set of
technologies that computer makers are using increasingly to
squeeze more speed out of their computers. But Sun has lagged
in pushing its Risc machines to run faster, allowing <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> and
<ORGANIZATION>H-P</ORGANIZATION> to surpass it in the performance race.
   Sun's new IPX, for example, runs at 24.2 "SPECmarks," a
widely used measure of a computer's speed in doing typical
tasks. H-P last <DATE>March</DATE> began selling a Risc machine that, at
about the same base price as <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s, runs at a faster 55.5
SPECmarks; <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s similarly priced RS/6000 Risc workstation
clocks in <MONEY>32.5 SPECmarks</MONEY>.
   Moreover, <ORGANIZATION>H-P</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> are juicing up their machines. <ORGANIZATION>H-P</ORGANIZATION>
said it will announce today it has begun shipping new
software that increases by about <PERCENT>7%</PERCENT> the speed of its Series
700 Risc workstations. <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Armonk</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, said it will begin
shipping software in <DATE>September</DATE> that will speed up its Risc
machines <PERCENT>27%</PERCENT>.
   Sun's "announcement does absolutely nothing to close the
performance gap," said <PERSON>Robert Weinberger</PERSON>,
workstation-marketing manager for <ORGANIZATION>H-P</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>.
   Sun also will face assaults on its own stronghold this
<DATE>fall</DATE>, when <ORGANIZATION>H-P</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Maynard</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, are expected to begin selling Risc machines for around
<MONEY>$5,000</MONEY>. On one hand, Sun's new workstations will help it sell
<PERCENT>47%</PERCENT> more machines in <DATE>1991</DATE> than in <DATE>1990</DATE>, estimates <PERSON>Ms. Battey</PERSON>
of <ORGANIZATION>International Data</ORGANIZATION>. But rivals' low-cost machines this
<DATE>fall</DATE> will be Sun's "first true competition," she says. "That
could stall the growth."
   Separately, <ORGANIZATION>Silicon Graphics</ORGANIZATION> said it will unveil a machine
it calls a "Risc personal computer," essentially a low-cost
version of the <ORGANIZATION>Mountain View</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, company's workstations
with multimedia technology added. The machine, dubbed <PERSON>IRIS
Indigo</PERSON>, lists from <MONEY>$7,995</MONEY> and can provide fancy, fast-moving
3-D images that, until now, only came from machines costing
several times that much.
   The machine can process and play music matching the
quality coming from digital-audio-tape players used by audio
buffs today, the company said. Along with other computer
makers, <ORGANIZATION>Silicon Graphics</ORGANIZATION> is aiming at what many expect to
become a booming market among business, schools and
laboratories for multimedia computers.
</TEXT>
