<HL> Sun Microsystems to Unveil Computers;
Stock Plummets Prior to Announcement
---
By Brenton R. Schlender
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 07/08/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> SUNW
COMPUTERS (EDP) </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> is slated to introduce today a new line of high-performance workstations that provide the horsepower of conventional minicomputers costing 10 times as much. 

   But despite the wide anticipation of <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s announcement, the company's share price plunged <MONEY>$5.25</MONEY>, to <MONEY>$35.125</MONEY> in national over-the-counter trading yesterday. 
Other technology stocks declined as well, though not as sharply as Sun shares. 
A Sun official said the company didn't have any explanation for the drop in the share price. 

   The new Sun-4 workstations, priced starting at <MONEY>$40,000</MONEY>, are tailored for computer-aided engineering and design uses, as well as for scientific modeling and calculation-intensive tasks. 
They are built around a new microprocessor Sun developed with the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> semiconductor unit of <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>. 
The new chip uses so-called RISC -- or reduced instruction set computer -- technology similar to that used in the new generation of computers made by <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co.</ORGANIZATION> and workstations made by <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp</ORGANIZATION>. 

   Moreover, in an unusual move, Sun said it will license <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu Microelectronics Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, and other chipmakers to sell the special RISC chip to other computer manufacturers. 
The plan is aimed at establishing an industry standard around Sun's workstation and software designs, much like personal computers follow design standards set by <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>. 

   Some analysts speculated that <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s share price fell because of the apparent riskiness of licensing its microprocessor designs to other chip makers, thus inviting companies to quickly replicate Sun's new machines. 
Others said that <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION> is expected to introduce a souped up version of its Micro VAX workstation later this year that will compete directly with Sun's new machine. 

   "This is an unprecedented move on <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s part that changes the rules of the game," said <PERSON>Richard Shaffer</PERSON>, publisher of <ORGANIZATION>Technologic Computer Letter</ORGANIZATION>. 
"Here you have a computer box company getting into the microprocessor design business that chip makers like <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Motorola Corp.</ORGANIZATION> have long dominated. 
It shows just how ambitious Sun is." 

   Indeed, the Sun-4 announcement is the latest in a flurry of new products and aggressive price-cutting actions taken by the <ORGANIZATION>Mountain View</ORGANIZATION>, Calif.-based company in recent months. 
In <DATE>April</DATE>, Sun chopped the price on its low-end workstation <PERCENT>37%</PERCENT> to less than <MONEY>$5,000</MONEY>, a move that has since been matched by its main competitors, <ORGANIZATION>Apollo Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment</ORGANIZATION>. 
The company also recently announced a line of communications products that can connect a full array of personal computers, workstations, minicomputers, mainframes and supercomputers. 
Later this year, the company is expected to introduce some new low-end machines. 

   The new workstation, which can cost almost <MONEY>$100,000</MONEY>, is 2 1/2 times more powerful than its predecessor, the Sun-3, though it costs only about <PERCENT>30%</PERCENT> more. 
It can handle 10 million instructions per second, or <ORGANIZATION>MIPS</ORGANIZATION>, which is faster than most superminicomputers. 

   Archrival Apollo, based in <LOCATION>Chelmsford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, generally has had more powerful workstations than Sun but doesn't have any products as fast as the Sun-4. 
However, rumors of <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s new workstation have been widely circulated. 
Last week, <PERSON>Edward Zander</PERSON>, vice president, marketing, at Apollo predicted his company would be back in the race soon. 
"By <DATE>early 1988</DATE>, we think you'll need 25 <ORGANIZATION>MIPS</ORGANIZATION>," he said. 

   The key to the speed of the Sun workstation is the RISC chip, which <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu</ORGANIZATION> helped design in this country, but makes in its Japanese plants. 
It marks the first time that a major <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> computer relied on a Japanese-made microprocessor. 

   "It's a sad state that Sun would have to turn to a Japanese chip maker," said <PERSON>Mr. Shaffer</PERSON>, "but the fact is, <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu</ORGANIZATION> makes crucial parts for a lot of this country's high performance computers." 

   According to <PERSON>Kenichi Katashiba</PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu Microelectronics</ORGANIZATION>, the RISC chip is the product of <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu</ORGANIZATION>'s advanced products division, which was established in <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION> in <DATE>1984</DATE> to develop semiconductors custom designed for American customers. 

   The RISC chip works faster because it has fewer basic functions to perform. 
Sun said its design will enable <ORGANIZATION>Fujitsu Microelectronics</ORGANIZATION> and other licensees, including <ORGANIZATION>Cypress Semiconductor Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Bipolar Integrated Technology Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, to further enhance the chip to make it even faster and more powerful while remaining compatible with all the software for existing machines. 
Likewise, the new Sun-4 machines can run the same software that Sun's previous Sun-3 and Sun-2 families use. 

   Sun is supplying special programs that convert programs from some 90 software companies into a form the new machines can understand. 
All of <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s computers use a version of <ORGANIZATION>American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s Unix operating system as the internal traffic cop routing data and instructions between the microprocessor and the workstation's screen, keyboard, printer and data storage devices. 

</TEXT>
