<HL>
   For Chip Makers, Much Is at Stake
</HL>
<DATE>
06/07/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   CPQ DEC DGN HIT HWP INTC J.TOS MIPS SUNW
</CO>
<MS>
INDUSTRIAL (IDU)
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
FAR EAST (FE)
JAPAN (JA)
MASSACHUSETTS (MA)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
TEXAS (TX)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   These are tumultuous times for makers of microprocessors,
the tiny chips that play central commander in desktop
computers.
   For a decade, Intel Corp. has dominated the market for
these brainy chips and has profited handsomely as demand
boomed for personal computers using Intel-designed chips.
Motorola Inc.'s chips have been a distant second, the chips
of choice for engineers' computers and for Apple's Macintosh.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But now a new breed of fast chips is threatening to bring
a change of guard, and to create a new set of winners and
losers in the computer market. The new chips use a technology
called reduced-instruction-set computing, or Risc, a term
used to describe a set of techniques for laying out circuitry
so that chips can perform calculations faster than with older
methods. Risc chips are rapidly winning favor with computer
makers because the chips offer far more speed at lower prices
than older chips offer.
   The power of Risc chips is showing up in the market. <ORGANIZATION>Sun
Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, an early leader in Risc chips, has quickly
gained No. 1 share of the workstation market using its Risc
chip. And Sun is making inroads into PC turf with low-cost
Risc workstations. <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co.</ORGANIZATION> unveiled a machine
using its own Risc chip in <DATE>March</DATE> that runs as much as 10
times faster than similarly priced systems using <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION>'s
latest chip.
   Intel-designed chips still go into <PERCENT>80%</PERCENT> of the PCs sold
world-wide, and the PC market is still 10 times bigger than
the workstation market. But computer makers see in Risc chips
an opportunity to recarve the computer-market pie.
   The big gamble: which of a half-dozen Risc chips to
choose. <ORGANIZATION>Compaq Computer Corp.</ORGANIZATION> has formed a loose alliance
with <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and others that sided with a
Risc chip designed by start-up <ORGANIZATION>Mips Computer Systems Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
<ORGANIZATION>Toshiba Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and several Taiwanese clone makers have chosen
Sun's chip. <ORGANIZATION>Hitachi Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> sides with <ORGANIZATION>HP</ORGANIZATION>'s chip; <ORGANIZATION>Data General
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> has chosen <ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION>'s, while <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> uses its own.
   The name of the game for the Risc-chip makers is to woo a
critical mass of computer makers; those who fail to win
allies will become also-rans, locked out of big-volume
markets. The game for computer makers is to bet which chip
will garner the most other computer makers, the most software
and the most users; those that bet on the wrong chip will be
left with warehouses full of machines that no one wants.
   (See related story: "Apple, <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> Discuss Swap of
Technology" -- WSJ <DATE>June 7, 1991</DATE>)
</TEXT>
