<HL> Sun Microsystems to Unveil Computers For General Use Based on 80386 Chip </HL>
<AUTHOR> Brenton R. Schlender (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> SUNW </CO>
<IN> EDP </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a maker of technical workstations, will announce today a new family of general-purpose computer workstations built around <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s popular 80386 microprocessor. 

   The new computers, with suggested prices starting at about <MONEY>$8,000</MONEY>, represent Sun's first foray into the crowded personal computer market and will give users the ability to run programs written for either of two popular computer operating systems -- <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s MS-DOS, which is widely used in most personal computers, and <ORGANIZATION>American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.</ORGANIZATION>'s Unix, which is the system of choice for engineering and scientific computers. 

   "Sun's new computers are a bridge between the commercial world of <ORGANIZATION>DOS</ORGANIZATION> and the technical world of Unix in a single box," said <PERSON>David Korus</PERSON>, a securities analyst for <ORGANIZATION>Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co.</ORGANIZATION> who follows the small computer systems industry. 
"It also further blurs the distinction between personal computers and workstations." 

   Workstations in the past have been used for sophisticated financial modeling and computer-aided engineering and design. 
Recently, price performance improvements have made them comparable in price to powerful personal computers. 

   Sun's introduction of the 386i family of computers had been widely rumored for months. 
"The timing just kind of happened," said <PERSON>Scott McNealy</PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION>Mountain View</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, company, who said the delay was due in part to "trying to understand the shortage of memory chips," which has been a nagging problem for Sun. 
Earlier this year, Sun had to raise prices on workstations as memory chip prices have climbed. 
Meanwhile chip shortages have caused Sun's backlog for its most popular computers to balloon to 120 days. 

   The new machines will come equipped with a monitor, a floppy disk-drive data storage device, a mouse pointing device, copies of both Unix and MS-DOS operating systems, circuitry necessary to plug the machine into a network and four megabytes of memory -- twice the amount provided by most competing personal computers using the <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION> 80386. 

   "We think our machine compares favorably with the <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> (<ORGANIZATION>Computer Corp.</ORGANIZATION>) 
Deskpro 386," said <PERSON>Mr. McNealy</PERSON>, referring to the first personal computer to incorporate the powerful <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION> chip. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> machine, priced from about <MONEY>$6,000</MONEY> and up, not including Unix, has been popular among power-hungry technical users and has far outsold competing machines. 

   Sun's new 386i family expands the company's family tree to include computers based on three different microprocessors, all using Unix. 
Sun started out building machines around <ORGANIZATION>Motorola Inc.</ORGANIZATION>'s 68000 family of microprocessors. 
Last year, Sun unveiled a high-performance chip called SPARC, for Scalable Processor architecture, that it uses in its most expensive and powerful workstations. 

   While Unix is the common thread among all three, analysts worry that three different hardware "architectures" might be too much for Sun to support. 
"The problem many computer companies run into is trying to do too many things to do any of them well," said <PERSON>Richard Shaffer</PERSON>, a computer industry analyst and consultant who publishes <ORGANIZATION>Technologic Computer Letter</ORGANIZATION>. 

   The 386i family presents other potential problems for Sun. 
If it catches on in a big way, it could exacerbate Sun's chip supply problems and perhaps cannibalize sales of its big-selling 3/60 workstation, which faces lengthy production delays. 

</TEXT>
