<HL> Sun Microsystems Unveils Low-Cost Sun-4 Workstation </HL>
<AUTHOR> Ken Wells (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> SUNW </CO>
<IN> EDP </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> introduced a low-cost version of its Sun-4 workstation that analysts say represents a price-for-performance breakthrough in the high-speed workstation field. 

   Known as the Sun-4/110, the machine is capable of handling seven million instructions per second and sells for <MONEY>$19,000</MONEY>, about <MONEY>$20,000</MONEY> less than a speedier version unveiled in <DATE>July</DATE>. 

   "That kind of performance for twenty grand" currently is unrivaled among workstation makers, said <PERSON>Richard Shaffer</PERSON>, editor of <ORGANIZATION>Technologic Computer Letter</ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based newsletter. 

   "This is a powerful machine for the price," added <PERSON>Lisa Thorell</PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION>Dataquest</ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION>Silicon Valley</ORGANIZATION> high technology market research firm. 
<PERSON>Ms. Thorell</PERSON> said a <ORGANIZATION>Dataquest</ORGANIZATION> analysis, assuming the Sun-4/110 performs as advertised, indicates that buyers seeking comparable performance would have to spend about double the cost of the machine. 

   Despite the bullishness of analysts, Sun's stock was battered in a general decline of high-technology issues. 
Sun closed yesterday at <MONEY>$29.75</MONEY> a share, down <MONEY>$2.50</MONEY> in national over-the-counter trading. 

   Sun said the new workstations are available immediately and would be shipped within 30 days of receipt of orders. 
It declined to estimate sales but said it has already sold about 1,000 units of its previously introduced Sun-4/200 series, which has a base price of about <MONEY>$39,000</MONEY>. 

   Sun said the low-cost workstations would be marketed to users in the financial analysis, artificial intelligence, medical imaging and computer-aided design fields. 
The basic Sun-4/110 is equipped with eight megabytes of memory and a monochrome monitor. 
Sun also said it would begin offering an optional 327-megabyte, 5 1/4-inch disk drive to add capacity to all of its Sun-4 workstations. 

   The Sun-4/110 represents the latest in a flurry of new products and aggressive price-cutting by the <ORGANIZATION>Mountain View</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, computer maker, whose machines are developed around superfast microchips known as RISC, or reduced instruction set computer. 
Sun, in its announcement, called the Sun-4/110 "the first supercomputing desktop computer," though not everyone buys that claim. 

   Though the definition of supercomputers is somewhat hazy, <PERSON>Mr. Shaffer</PERSON> said Sun's claims for the Sun-4/110 are "something of a stretch" since supercomputers currently are generally considered to have much faster processing speeds than the <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION> unit. 

</TEXT>
