<HEAD>IBM's New Workstations Enter Fast-Growing Market It's Never
Mastered</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> unveiled a line of computer workstations
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> that the company says outperform and underprice the
competition and should help it snare a major stake in a
fast-growing market where it never had success.
   ``The opportunity is big _ it's growing at over <PERCENT>30 percent</PERCENT> a
year, and it's mostly a new opportunity for <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>,'' said President
<PERSON>Jack D. Kuehler</PERSON>.
   The machines, called the RISC System-6000, also mark the first
time that the world's largest computer maker has wholeheartedly
embraced the Unix computer operating system that is fast becoming
the industry standard.
   <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION> also announced its
intention to provide ways to link the new machines with <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>
computers that run on its proprietary operating system.
   An operating system is software that controls basic computer
functions, such as executing commands from the keyboard and opening
computer files.
   <PERSON>Kuehler</PERSON> told a news conference that the new machines, designed
for use by engineers, ``outperform the newest and best that our
competitors offer.''
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> announced four high-performance workstations and five
file-servers, which are used to link computers in a network. The
machines range in price from about <MONEY>$13,000</MONEY> to more than <MONEY>$74,000</MONEY>.
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> said the lowest-price model is the most powerful desktop
workstation on the market, beating the offering of <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, considered the workstation leader. The <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> model performs
27.5 million instructions per second, or mips, compared with 12.5
mips for the Sun model. It also is slightly cheaper than Sun's.
   Industry analysts say the workstations are impressive for their
performance, pricing and features.
   ``From the customer standpoint, I think it's going to get <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>
into the door in ways it didn't before,'' said <PERSON>Peter Burris</PERSON>, an
analyst for <ORGANIZATION>International Data Corp.</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Framingham</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass</LOCATION>.
   Workstations are desktop or side-of-desk machines that are much
more powerful than personal computers. Some even match the power of
mainframes. They are used for such processing-intensive tasks as
three-dimensional computer modeling of new products.
   The workstation market is small, but is among the
fastest-growing computer segments, and uses for the machines are
expanding.
   ``A lot of things start in the scientific market and gravitate
out toward other markets,'' said <PERSON>Barry Bosak</PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION>Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> introduced a workstation line several years ago, the RT
line, but it captured less than <PERCENT>3 percent</PERCENT> of market. Experts
consider the machines underpowered and overpriced.
   ``We made a mistake,'' <PERSON>Kuehler</PERSON> said in an interview.
   The workstation field is dominated by <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co</ORGANIZATION>.
   Unix, developed by <ORGANIZATION>American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.</ORGANIZATION>, allows
machines from different manufacturers to work together. Until now,
<ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> had promoted its own operating systems. Basing the workstations
on Unix shows <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> is serious about this market, <PERSON>Kuehler</PERSON> said in the
interview.
   It also is recognition of the huge library of Unix-based
software available for workstations, he said.
   The machines are based on <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s own version of Unix, called <LOCATION>AIX</LOCATION>,
but are a new generation of the operating system. Analysts said the
new <LOCATION>AIX</LOCATION> is even more compatible with industry standards.
   Unix-based applications programs _ the software that provides
the actual uses of computers, such as word processing _ must be
rewritten for <LOCATION>AIX</LOCATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> has been working with software companies for some time to
develop programs for the new machines. By the end of the year,
about 1,500 application programs worldwide will be available, it
said.
   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s embrace of Unix has broad implications for the operating
standard, said <PERSON>Louise Rehling</PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION>SPSS
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> software company that was among those recruited.
   ``We think <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> is going to bring a lot of credibility to the
Unix markeplace,'' she said. ``The size of the pie will grow as
well as the <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> share.''
   Like the older <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> workstations, the new models are based on
reduced-instruction-set computing technology, or RISC, which
simplifies the circuitry of a computer's central processor to
increase speed and offer cost savings. But <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> said the RISC system
in the new machines is greatly improved.
   Shipments of the workstations will begin within 90 days, <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>
said.
   <PERSON>Bosak</PERSON> said the workstations would have little short-term impact
on <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s earnings. But they represent an important signal that the
company is working to improve its fortunes.
   Last month, <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> reported its <DATE>1989</DATE> profit slipped <PERCENT>35 percent</PERCENT> from
the year before. The company also has embarked on a cost-cutting
program that involves the elimination of thousands of jobs.
</TEXT>
