<HL> Technology Brief -- Sun Microsystems Inc.: Workstation Prices Increased To Reflect Component Costs </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> SUNW </CO>
<IN> EDP </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> said it raised prices on its workstations by an average of <PERCENT>7%</PERCENT>, passing on to customers the higher cost for computer components such as <ORGANIZATION>DRAM</ORGANIZATION> memory chips. 

   Sun's move follows the trend of recent price increases by such companies as <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Apple Computer</ORGANIZATION>. 

   The increase, for example, raises the price of Sun's entry level workstation, the Sun-3/50, to <MONEY>$5495</MONEY> from <MONEY>$4995</MONEY>. 
Also raised <PERCENT>7%</PERCENT> were prices for Sun's file server products. 
System prices for newer products were raised an average of <PERCENT>6%</PERCENT>, while prices for older product lines were hiked by <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>15%</PERCENT>. 

   Sun, based in <LOCATION>Mountain View</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, said the increased prices will help the company purchase larger quantities of memory components, thereby increasing manufacturing and driving down "unacceptably long lead times" for its products. 

</TEXT>
