<HL>
   Technology:
   Sun's Anti-Clone Decree Sparks Anger,
   Charges of Hypocrisy on `Open Systems'
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/29/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   SUNW
</CO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
OTHER SPECIALTY RETAILERS OF LIMITED PRODUCT LINES (OTS)
ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)
</IN>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
</RE>
<LP>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. has long proclaimed a gospel of
openness, urging computer makers to convert to Sun-designed
computer chips and to freely clone Sun's machines. Now irate
Sun allies say the Mountain View, Calif.-based computer maker
isn't practicing what it preaches.
   At issue is a new Sun mandate that bars dealers of Sun
machines from carrying clones, machines that mimic Sun's.
Sun's new commandment, issued earlier this month, comes just
as clones of Sun's popular Sparcstation computers are
beginning to break into the market.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sun's new decree, "is very hypocritical," says <PERSON>Tony
Siress</PERSON>, a director at <ORGANIZATION>Single Source</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>,
dealer of Sun machines that also carries clones made by
<LOCATION>Taiwan</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Tatung Science and Technology Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Mr. Siress</PERSON> and other dealers are steamed because Sun has
long promised not to block companies from cloning Sun's
workstations, high-performance computers often used by
engineers. Sun, despite its No. 1 share of the workstation
market last year, needs clones to help it reach its goal of
establishing its Sparc chip as the chip of choice in a broad
range of computer markets. Sun's aim is to replay the
personal-computer-market scenario, in which millions of
clones of <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s PC made the
<ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> design a de facto standard.
   The new Sun directive, which <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION> says took effect <DATE>April
20</DATE>, prohibits Sun's so-called value-added-resellers --
authorized dealers in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> that package Sun machines with
other software and hardware -- from selling all clones except
lap-top machines, which Sun doesn't make.
   Sun's clone ban has sparked righteous indignation in
trade-press editorials and brought gleeful reactions from
executives at <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION> rivals such as <ORGANIZATION>Mips Computer Systems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>
of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Mips</ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON>Robert Miller</PERSON> and others
have long labeled as false and misleading Sun's claim that it
espouses the new industry religion of "open systems," in
which computer makers build machines using freely available
standards.
   A Sun spokesman says <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s clone veto is perfectly legal
and was enforced to prevent clone makers from stealing a free
ride off of <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s large investment in its dealer channels,
which include about 400 value-added resellers, or VARs. "Just
because we have open systems doesn't mean we have to open our
channels up to competitive clone vendors," the spokesman
says.
   Some Sun dealers agree. Sun "has made a big investment in
training of VARs," says <PERSON>Patricia Shanks</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>Basis
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION>Emeryville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, Sun reseller that specializes in
government contracts. "I think it's fair for them to try to
protect that investment."
   Sun's ban is "perfectly legitimate," as long as certain
conditions exist, says <PERSON>Laurence Popofsky</PERSON>, an antitrust lawyer
with the <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> firm <ORGANIZATION>Heller, Ehrman, White &amp;
McAuliffe</ORGANIZATION>. There must be, for example, other sales channels
available to clone makers, he says. Sun resellers say there
are thousands more non-Sun resellers to which clone makers
can turn.
   But legal or not, Sun's prohibition robs resellers of
potential customers who probably will now turn to cut-rate
dealers, says <PERSON>Victor Leventhal</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>CAD Solutions
Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a Sun reseller in <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> "I'm offended," says
<PERSON>Mr. Leventhal</PERSON>, who planned to sell Sun clones. "That's not
the gentlemanly way of doing it -- you win by the best
products, the best support, the best price; you don't win
because you limit distribution."
   Clone makers are equally piqued. The Sun ban is aimed at
hurting the several dozen clone makers Sun wooed into its
camp, says <PERSON>Mark Johnson</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>Opus Systems</ORGANIZATION>, a
<LOCATION>Cupertino</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, Sun-clone maker. "We have a situation
where {Sun} has been overly zealous creating barriers for
their own channel," says <PERSON>Mr. Johnson</PERSON>, who adds that Opus is
"looking at legal options."
   The Sun move adds to already smoldering criticism among
allies and rivals alike that <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION> is engaged in conflict of
interest, enticing computer makers to its Sparc-chip
technology on one hand and, on the other hand, selling
workstations that use leading-edge Sparc chips that aren't
yet available to clone makers.
   Sun, attempting to help stanch some such criticism, plans
to split off certain software and hardware-licensing
businesses into two subsidiaries. The new units, Sun argues,
will operate independently of the parent and should allay
fears that Sun unfairly favors its own machines.
   ---
   <PERSON>G. Pascal Zachary</PERSON> contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
