<HL>
   Technology &amp; Medicine:
   Hewlett, Motorola Will Sell Workstations
   Through Dealers Who Target Businesses
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
10/07/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   HWP INEL MICA MOT
</CO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS OF LIMITED PRODUCT LINES (OTS)
ALL SPECIALTY RETAILERS (RTS)
</IN>
<RE>
ARIZONA (AZ)
CALIFORNIA (CA)
ILLINOIS (IL)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PENNSYLVANIA (PA)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   Makers of the high-speed computers called workstations,
long envious of the huge markets that personal computers
enjoy, are taking a stab at PC turf by signing up dealers
that sell PCs to businesses.
   The latest entries are Hewlett-Packard Co. and Motorola
Inc., each of which plans to announce this week that it has
agreed to sell workstations through mass-market dealer
MicroAge Inc. of Tempe, Ariz. Hewlett also plans to sell
through Intelligent Electronics of Exton, Pa., a dealer that,
as does MicroAge, sells Hewlett's PCs, laser printers and
calculators.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Both companies see their foray into the "dealer channel"
as a big step toward broadening the appeal of their
workstations beyond traditional markets among engineers and
technicians. They follow such companies as <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems
Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, which have already signed
on such dealers.
   "Wide-scale distribution is a critical factor going
forward into the <DATE>1990s</DATE>," said <PERSON>Douglas Kass</PERSON>, an analyst at
<ORGANIZATION>Dataquest Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a market research firm. "To have their
machines more commercially accepted, this is the best method
they could devise."
   Until now, <PERSON>Hewlett</PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION> have sold their
workstations through direct sales forces or so-called
value-added resellers, highly specialized dealers that tend
to sell complex packages of computer equipment, software and
service. Resellers are good at selling computer systems to
traditional technical markets, but lack extensive experience
and a broad clientele among businesses.
   That was a crucial point for <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett</ORGANIZATION>, which introduced a
super-fast workstation called the Series 700 in <DATE>March</DATE> that
was so unexpectedly popular that the <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>,
company still can't keep up with demand. Hewlett plans to
pitch the Series 700 and certain other workstations to
business users through selected <ORGANIZATION>MicroAge</ORGANIZATION> and Intelligent
stores beginning <DATE>January 1992</DATE>. "We needed to find broader
ways to get to customers," said <PERSON>Alan Arnette</PERSON>, who manages
sales channels for <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett</ORGANIZATION>'s workstation division. "We'd be
self-limiting with existing channels."
   <ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Schaumburg</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ill.</LOCATION>, will use <ORGANIZATION>MicroAge</ORGANIZATION> to sell a
type of workstation called a server, which businesses use to
tie desktop computers into networks and data bases. The
<ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION> machines, called the MultiPersonal Series 8000, are
designed to allow <ORGANIZATION>Apple Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION>'s Macintosh machines to
tap into networks that include machines from other computer
makers. <ORGANIZATION>MicroAge</ORGANIZATION>, with about 900 stores nationwide, is a big
seller of Macintosh systems.
   The target, said <PERSON>Wayne Sennett</PERSON>, general manager of
<ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Commercial Systems Division</ORGANIZATION>, is the large and
small businesses that the company couldn't cover before. "It
gives us national access for our products and a much broader
base of customers," he said.
   Hewlett-Packard and <ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION> may be reacting to pressure
from rivals, analysts said. Sun Microsystems, <ORGANIZATION>Mountain View</ORGANIZATION>,
<LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, has sold workstations through <ORGANIZATION>MicroAge</ORGANIZATION> and
Intelligent since <DATE>July 1990</DATE>. Digital, <LOCATION>Maynard</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, also
has begun using a dealer channel, putting pressure on <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett</ORGANIZATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON>Mr. Kass</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Dataquest</ORGANIZATION>. "They're playing
catch-up," said <PERSON>Mr. Kass</PERSON>, adding that <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett</ORGANIZATION> needs to sign
up more stores quickly to compete with rivals.
</TEXT>
