<HL>
   Technology:
   Compaq, Microsoft Plan Industry Group
   To Create Standard for Workstations
   ----
   By Jim Bartimo and Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
02/11/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   CPQ MSFT SUNW DEC INTC MOT MIPS
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Compaq Computer Corp. and Microsoft Corp. are piecing
together an industry coalition to attack the fast-growing
workstation market now led by Sun Microsystems Inc.
   The group hopes to bring together at least five computer
companies, including Digital Equipment Corp., to create a new
standard design for workstations, said people familiar with
the discussions. Today's workstations -- more powerful than
personal computers and often used by scientists and engineers
-- lack the kind of de facto software standard that has made
personal computers so successful.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If it succeeds, the coalition could rob market share from
Sun and from companies such as <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Motorola Inc.</ORGANIZATION>,
which make the microprocessor chips that operate most of
today's desktop computers. But it will surely face powerful
opposition from <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Motorola</ORGANIZATION>, each of which plans to
unveil new super-chips this year and next.
   Because of the expected slowdown in personal computer
sales in <DATE>1991</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> and other personal computer makers have
been searching for a hot technology to lure buyers. And
workstations are expected to grow at a continued faster pace.
The industry group has already sketched out a preliminary
blueprint for their workstation, sources say, but isn't
expected to announce its plans for at least a month and won't
market the workstations for more than a year.
   If the group proceeds, <ORGANIZATION>Santa Cruz Operations Inc.</ORGANIZATION> would
develop crucial operating-system software and <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> would
provide a version of its popular Windows operating software.
The electronic brains of the workstation will be a powerful
microprocessor using reduced-instruction-set-computing. This
RISC technology allows chips to operate faster by reducing
their complexity. The favored candidate is the R4000 chip
announced earlier this month by its designer, <ORGANIZATION>Mips Computer
Systems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, industry experts say.
   A decision to standardize on the R4000 chip would be a
bonanza for <ORGANIZATION>Mips</ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>. But the company's
president, <PERSON>Robert Miller</PERSON>, reached by phone <DATE>Saturday</DATE>,
cautioned that talk of <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> and others agreeing to
standardize on the chip "is still speculative."
   Such a workstation alliance would be a blow to <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>, which
quickly became the biggest maker of workstations in the late
<DATE>1980s</DATE>, but now could be forced to compete with several strong
companies backing a single alternative design. People
familiar with the group's discussions said the Sun-designed
Sparc chip, which also employs RISC, has been ruled out
despite heavy pressure from Sun on <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> to use the chip.
   Any coalition must contend with <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION>'s technological and
marketing might. By the time the industry alliance produces
its first machine, <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION> will have announced its new 80586
chip and shipped faster versions of its 80486 chip. Both
<ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION> chips will adhere to existing industry standards.
   In <DATE>1988</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> and other companies banded together to
develop a PC standard known as <ORGANIZATION>Extended Industry Standard
Architecture</ORGANIZATION>. The so-called "Gang of Nine" successfully
developed and built EISA PCs to compete with the standard set
by <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION> known as the <ORGANIZATION>Micro
Channel Architecture</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Microsoft</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Mips</ORGANIZATION> officials refused to comment on
the existence of the group.
   ---
   <PERSON>G. Pascal Zachary</PERSON> contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
