<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Sun Microsystems' Net Jumps 35%;
   Record Shipments of Workstations Cited
   ----
   By Stephen Kreider Yoder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/09/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   SUNW
</CO>
<MS>
TECHNOLOGY (TEC)
</MS>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<NS>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</NS>
<RE>
CALIFORNIA (CA)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. -- Sun Microsystems Inc. reported a
35% jump in fiscal fourth-quarter net income, citing record
shipments of its workstation computers and improved profit
margins.
   Sun's earnings contrast with the recent poor showings of
big personal-computer makers such as Compaq Computer Corp.
and attest to Sun's dominant grip on the fast-growing market
for workstations, the high-speed engineering computers that
are increasingly favored in business computing.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sun said its net income for the <DATE>quarter ended June 30</DATE> was
<MONEY>$66.4 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>63 cents</MONEY> a share, up from <MONEY>$49.1 million</MONEY>, or
<MONEY>51 cents</MONEY> a share, in the year-ago quarter. Revenue was <MONEY>$942.5
million</MONEY>, up <PERCENT>35%</PERCENT> from <MONEY>$700.1 million</MONEY>.
   <PERSON>Kevin Melia</PERSON>, Sun's chief financial officer, said in a
statement that the computer maker saw good results in the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Pacific Rim</LOCATION>. Sun shipped a record 49,000
machines in the quarter, he said.
   Sun, the world's biggest workstation seller, is scrabbling
with rivals such as <ORGANIZATION>Mips Computer Systems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Sunnyvale</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, in an
increasingly fierce battle to woo a broad range of
desktop-computer users who traditionally use PCs or terminals
tied to massive mainframe computers. Such competition has
begun trimming profit margins for workstations, much as price
wars have trimmed profits in PCs and plagued such companies
as <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>International Business
Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Armonk</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>N.Y.</LOCATION>, with poor earnings.
   Despite increased competition at the low-priced end of the
workstation market, where Sun's biggest strength lies, Sun
reported that its operating-profit margin in the <DATE>fourth
quarter</DATE> was the highest in three years, <PERCENT>10.7%</PERCENT>.
   Sun's <DATE>fourth-quarter</DATE> profit was close to most analysts'
estimates. Sun's stock closed at <MONEY>$32.25</MONEY>, down <MONEY>$1.875</MONEY>, in
national over-the-counter trading yesterday.
   However, <PERSON>Mr. Melia</PERSON> said Sun is "cautious" in its outlook
for the fiscal <DATE>1992</DATE> first half, in part because of the
"overall volatility of the industry." He warned investors not
to expect sequential gains in revenue or profit, especially
in its <DATE>first quarter</DATE>.
   For all of fiscal <DATE>1991</DATE>, Sun reported a <PERCENT>71%</PERCENT> jump in net
income to <MONEY>$190.3 million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>$1.85</MONEY> a share, from <MONEY>$111.2
million</MONEY>, or <MONEY>$1.21</MONEY> a share, in fiscal <DATE>1990</DATE>. Revenue rose <PERCENT>31%</PERCENT>
to <MONEY>$3.22 billion</MONEY> from <MONEY>$2.47 billion</MONEY>.
   Sun said it ended the fiscal year with <MONEY>$834 million</MONEY> in
cash.
</TEXT>
