<HL> Compaq to Introduce Speedier Versions
Of Portables, Desktops Using 80386 Chip
---
By Paul Duke Jr.
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 09/24/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> CPQ
COMPUTERS (EDP)
ELECTRIC, ELECTRONICS, APPLIANCES (ELE) </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Compaq Computer Corp.</ORGANIZATION> is expected to introduce next week speedier versions of its top-of-the-line portable and desktop computers. 

   The moves are <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>'s first product introductions since <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION> revamped its personal computer line in <DATE>April</DATE> and indicate that <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> is following its tested strategy of trying to leapfrog <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> performance and concentrate on high-powered business computers. 

   At the same time, <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> apparently hasn't moved to copy some of the deviations from the standard-setting <DATE>1981</DATE> <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> design that the computer giant made in <DATE>April</DATE>, a sign that the Houston-based company believes there is still a big and lucrative market for computers based on the earlier design. 
<ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> personal computers -- as well as those from other big makers like <ORGANIZATION>Tandy Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.</ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION>Leading Edge Products Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, for instance -- are built around the six-year-old IBM-PC design. 

   Industry sources expect <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> to introduce an update of its Deskpro 386 computer using a faster version of the <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION> 80386 microprocessor, known as a 386 chip, that powers the current Deskpro 386 models. 
The new version, also made by <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION>, will operate <PERCENT>25%</PERCENT> faster than previous 386 chips, which will speed up software programs run on the computer. 

   The microprocessor is the "brain" of the computer, which electronically performs the computer's operations. 
The <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION> 386 chip is currently the most powerful microprocessor available for IBM-compatible computers. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> officials wouldn't discuss the new products, which are expected to be introduced at a news conference the company has scheduled for next <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> announced in <DATE>April</DATE> a computer scheduled to be available in the <DATE>fourth quarter</DATE> with a 386 chip running at the same speed as <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>'s expected models. 
It isn't clear when <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>'s computers would reach stores, but <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> models generally have hit the market within a few weeks after introduction. 
Sources familiar with the expected <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> announcement weren't sure of the prices for the new models. 
<ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>'s current Deskpro 386 models start at about <MONEY>$7,000</MONEY> including a monitor; the price of the new machine is likely to be slighly higher. 

   The move to the faster chips is yet another step in the growth of personal computer power, as small desktop units increasingly take over tasks that only a few years ago required larger, free-standing minicomputers. 
The faster chip will make personal computers more attractive for use in architecture, design, or industrial management applications that use big, complicated software programs that bog down on less-powerful microcomputers. 

   That market has been served by workstation makers like <ORGANIZATION>Apollo Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc</ORGANIZATION>. 
A workstation is a powerful personal computer for engineers and other professionals that is faster and has better graphics and communications links than office desktop computers. 

   One industry source, who asked not to be identified, said <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> would offer as an option on the new models a graphics device that incorporates some workstation technology. 

   "It'll give (the <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> entries) the amazing graphics that have so far been available only on workstations. 
And it should be better even than the improved graphics on the new <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> line," the source said. 

   <PERSON>Tim Bajarin</PERSON>, vice president of the Creative Strategies market research firm in <LOCATION>Santa Clara</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, said, "<ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>'s move will create a big collision with the workstation market. 
It's the first time you'll have a (personal computer) with workstation power." 

   While <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> is improving its graphics to match advances made by <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> in its <DATE>April</DATE> line, sources said the <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> models won't mimic the most important change in the new <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> computer -- the "microchannel," <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s term for the pathway between the parts of the computer that actually perform computations and other parts like the memory, storage, modems and printers. 
The microchannel has caused some controversy in the computer industry because it smoothes out the pathway used in previous models, but at the cost of making obsolete some peripheral devices, such as modems, which worked with computers based on the <DATE>1981</DATE> design. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> had said <DATE>earlier this year</DATE> it planned to introduce at least one computer that didn't copy the new pathway. 
In doing so next week, <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> will be directly challenging <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION>'s new line in the big business market. 
That is a sign of <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION>'s belief that buyers still aren't completely enamored of the new <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> line, and also, perhaps, that the new <ORGANIZATION>IBM</ORGANIZATION> computers are proving more difficult to copy both technically and legally than the old line. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> is also expected to announce a version of its popular Portable III model with the 386 chip, a machine that has been expected for months. 
<ORGANIZATION>Compaq</ORGANIZATION> was the first major manufacturer to introduce a personal computer using the 386 <DATE>last year</DATE>, but it won't be the first to introduce a portable with the chip. 
<ORGANIZATION>Toshiba Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> a few weeks ago introduced in <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> the first portable to use the 386 chip; the model isn't yet available in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> IBM doesn't offer a portable with the 386 chip. 

</TEXT>
