<HEAD>Matsushita Says Ally To Use AT&amp;T-Sun Design</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Matsushita Electric Industrial Co.</ORGANIZATION> is lining up on
the side of <ORGANIZATION>American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems
Inc.</ORGANIZATION> in a high-stakes competition over a critical piece of computer
software.
   <PERSON>Matsushita</PERSON> said <DATE>Monday</DATE> that a close <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> business ally has
concluded a licensing agreement with <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION> and Sun to use their
Sparc computer architecture in a new engineering workstation.
   The Sparc design is tailored for use with <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION>'s latest version
of Unix. Unix is a base layer of software that allows programs to
run on a variety of computer models.
   The version of Unix developed by <ORGANIZATION>AT&amp;T</ORGANIZATION> with Sun has been
challenged by an industry group that says the popular software
should not be controlled by one company. That group includes such
powerhouses as <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Digital
Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co</ORGANIZATION>.
   <PERSON>Matsushita</PERSON>'s decision to jump into the fast-growing workstation
market ends an effective 24-year absence from the field of
high-powered computers. Workstations are fast computers with strong
graphics capabilities that are typically used by scientists and
engineers.
   <PERSON>Matsushita</PERSON> said it plans to build the central processing unit
for the workstations designed by <ORGANIZATION>Solbourne Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of
<LOCATION>Longmont</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colo.</LOCATION>, and Solbourne would supply the rest of the
workstation's components and sell it under its own brand name in
the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Matsushita</PERSON> owns <PERCENT>52 percent</PERCENT> of Solbourne, according to <PERSON>Mike
Kitadeya</PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON>Matsushita</PERSON>'s <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> subsidiary.
   Solbourne hopes to put a workstation on sale in the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> early next year, <PERSON>Kitadeya</PERSON> said.
   <PERSON>Matsushita</PERSON>'s decision to enter the fray over Unix, though
indirectly for the time being, on the side of Sparc could affect
the opinions of other Japanese electronics makers.
</TEXT>
