<HL> 

Units by Digital
Equipment Seen
---
Concern Is Expected to Add
Competitive Computers
To Its Engineering Line
---
By William M. Bulkeley
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 02/06/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> DEC
COMPUTERS (EDP) </IN>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION> is expected next week to unveil low-priced computers and workstations in its popular VAX line that will make the company much more competitive with other makers of engineering computers. 

   Industry analysts and competitors said they expect the new systems to have base prices around <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> -- half the price of <ORGANIZATION>Maynard</ORGANIZATION>, Mass.-based <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION>'s current low-priced systems -- and to compete head-to-head with low-priced workstations made by <ORGANIZATION>Apollo Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Chelmsford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Mountain View</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>. 

   The new products, which <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> insiders said were originally supposed to be ready <DATE>last year</DATE>, are expected to help <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> recapture market share in the low-priced end of the engineering and scientific market. 
"They'll be able to position themselves much more competitively. 
They won't be technological leaders, but they don't have to be," said <PERSON>Vicki Brown</PERSON>, a market researcher at <ORGANIZATION>International Data Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Framingham</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass</LOCATION>. 
She said many customers who use larger Digital systems also will buy the low-priced VAX computers because they can run the same software the larger systems do. 

   Digital said it has scheduled a news conference in <LOCATION>Boston</LOCATION> for next <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> to announce "two new major additions to" its VAX line. 
The company declined further comment. 

   Digital Review, a biweekly Boston-based publication that covers the company, will report in its <DATE>Monday</DATE> edition that <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> will announce a workstation called the VAXstation <DATE>2000</DATE> with a base price of <MONEY>$10,125</MONEY>, without a disk storage device. 
The publication also will report that the other computer is the MicroVAX <DATE>2000</DATE>, a system that can be used by as many as four users at separate terminals, with a base price of <MONEY>$9,100</MONEY>. 

   Analysts and consultants say the VAXstation <DATE>2000</DATE> is a particularly important product for <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> because the company has been struggling in the booming market for engineering workstations. 
Engineers use workstations, which display drawings well, as personal computers for designing products and writing software. 

   International Data estimates the overall workstation market nearly doubled in size last year to <MONEY>$1.4 billion</MONEY>. 
The leaders in the overall market, according to another research firm, <ORGANIZATION>Dataquest Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, are Apollo, with a <PERCENT>26%</PERCENT> share; Sun, with <PERCENT>23%</PERCENT>, and <ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Palo Alto</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, with <PERCENT>17%</PERCENT>. 
<ORGANIZATION>Dataquest</ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> had only <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> of the market last year. 

   Apollo, which founded the workstation market, said its lowest-priced product, the <MONEY>$9,900</MONEY> model DN3000, "is one of the most successful products in the computer industry." 
A spokesman added that the company doesn't think the <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> introduction will hurt. 
"A lot of customers have been aware of this <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> product. 
If there was going to be an impact, we would have felt it by now." 

   Fast-growing <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems</ORGANIZATION> makes a diskless workstation, the 3/50, with a base price of <MONEY>$7,900</MONEY>. 
<PERSON>Cynthia Typaldos</PERSON>, a marketing manager, said, "We haven't seen any impact." 
She said reports of <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION>'s system costing <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> indicate it won't be competitive in price, "and I suspect it won't in performance either." 

   In composite trading on the <ORGANIZATION>New York Stock Exchange</ORGANIZATION> yesterday, <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> shares closed at <MONEY>$150.375</MONEY>, up <MONEY>$3.75</MONEY>. 
In national over-the-counter trading, Apollo closed at <MONEY>$20.50</MONEY>, down <MONEY>$1.125</MONEY>, and <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems</ORGANIZATION> closed at <MONEY>$28.75</MONEY>, down <MONEY>$1.125</MONEY>. 

   One analyst who studies <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> for another computer company said the product "will sell to their customer base. 
Whether they steal people from Sun and Apollo depends on" the customer. 

   While other workstation makers design computers that use standard chips from <ORGANIZATION>Motorola Corp.</ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> custom designs its own chips so the computers will run <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION>'s proprietary software. 
It is important for <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> to be able to sell low-priced hardware that runs <ORGANIZATION>VAX</ORGANIZATION> programs or its customers might be tempted to switch. 

   <PERSON>Jonathan Cohler</PERSON>, editor of <ORGANIZATION>Digital Review</ORGANIZATION>, said he thinks <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> also tried to price the VAXstation <DATE>2000</DATE> low enough to forestall inroads into its market by the expected new generation of workstations that are being designed around <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION>'s 80386 chip. 
<ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, among many others, is expected to pursue the engineering-workstation market with a computer based on that chip. 

</TEXT>
