<LP>
   Sun Microsystems Inc. and Cray Research Inc. plan to
announce today a technology agreement that could make the two
computer concerns a bigger force in the rapidly growing
market for "parallel" supercomputers that chain together
scores of processor chips.
   Industry officials familiar with the plans said Cray has
agreed to use Sun's Sparc architecture in future
supercomputers, probably in machines that chain together many
microprocessors, or "brain" chips, in a format often called
parallel supercomputing. Whatever machines come from the
deal, however, aren't likely to be on the market for several
years, industry analysts said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Sun spokeswoman acknowledged that Sun plans a press
conference with <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION> to announce a "technology-sharing and
marketing agreement," but wouldn't provide details. A <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION>
spokesman would only say it will announce a "strategic
relationship" soon.
   For <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>'s Sparc chips offer a weapon against
upstart supercomputer makers, such as <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION>Santa
Clara</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>Thinking Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION>Cambridge</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, which are quickly gaining market share with their
parallel machines. <ORGANIZATION>Thinking Machines</ORGANIZATION> earlier agreed to use
Sparc chips in future parallel machines, which are popular
among scientists and financial institutions because the
machines are far less expensive than traditional
supercomputers.
   "Cray needs to be in this marketplace and they know it,
and the way to get there is to work with Sun," said <PERSON>Debra
Goldfarb</PERSON>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION>International Data Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, a research
concern.
   Industry analysts say sales of <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION>'s older line machines,
which can use only a few processors at once, have remained
flat for several years. <ORGANIZATION>Intel</ORGANIZATION>, by contrast, says sales of its
supercomputers, which can connect as many as 4,000 internal
processors, have doubled every year since <DATE>1989</DATE>.
   Cray's endorsement of Sparc gives Sun, Mountain View,
<LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, a high-profile ally in its effort to woo a wide range
of computer makers to its architecture. Sun's Sparc has been
the dominant chip in low-end workstation computers used by
engineers, but the company is trying to penetrate higher-end
markets.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION> relationship will also give Sun the technology it
needs to speed up its Sparc chip, which has been overshadowed
recently by faster chips from such companies as
<ORGANIZATION>Hewlett-Packard Co.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON>Ms. Goldfarb</PERSON>. The deal isn't likely to affect as
yet unannounced plans by <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION> to use a <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment
Corp.</ORGANIZATION> chip in some future machines, she added.
   <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION>'s announcement of its support of Sparc comes as the
<LOCATION>Minneapolis</LOCATION> company completes its acquisition of <ORGANIZATION>Floating
Point Systems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION>Beaverton</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ore.</LOCATION>, supercomputer maker
that unsuccessfully attempted to extract itself from
financial troubles by developing parallel machines with Sparc
chips.
   ---
   <PERSON>Karen Blumenthal</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> contributed to this article.
   ---
   <ORGANIZATION>Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   DEBRA GOLDFARB</ORGANIZATION>, an analyst at <ORGANIZATION>International Data Corp.</ORGANIZATION>,
believes <ORGANIZATION>Cray Research Inc.</ORGANIZATION>'s agreement to use <ORGANIZATION>Sun
Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>'s microchips could help <ORGANIZATION>Cray</ORGANIZATION> penetrate the
market for "moderately parallel" supercomputers that chain
together a number of so-called Risc chips but won't
necessarily involve development of "massively parallel"
machines. In the <DATE>Jan. 22</DATE> edition, her position was
misconstrued.
