<HEAD>Company Unveils 3-D Technology for Personal Computers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Silicon Graphics Corp.</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> unveiled
technology the company said will give personal computer users
access to three-dimensional graphics previously available only on
expensive computer workstations.
   The company announced circuit boards that fit inside
<ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION> and IBM-compatible personal
computers that use <ORGANIZATION>Intel Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s powerful 80386 and 80486
microprocessors.
   The boards, called Irisvision, allow users to move and alter 3-D
color images on the screen and instantly see the changes they make,
a feature important to scientists and engineers.
   ``Irisvision redefines and sets new standards for personal
computer graphics,'' said <PERSON>Edward R. McCracken</PERSON>, Silicon Graphics'
president and chief executive officer. ``(It) will change the way
people use PCs for design and animation.''
   Both the boards and about 15 software packages to take advantage
of them will be available in <DATE>January</DATE>, the company said. More than
20 software developers are writing applications for Irisvision, it
added.
   Silicon Graphics is known for its 3-D graphics computers,
ranging from workstations starting at <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> to supercomputers
costing <MONEY>$500,000</MONEY>. The boards are the first product the fast-growing
9-year-old Mountain View company has produced for the personal
computer market.
   They also come as competitors, notably <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION>,
try to woo personal computer users with cheaper workstations.
   Irisvision boards will cost <MONEY>$3,500</MONEY> to <MONEY>$5,000</MONEY>. The company hopes
to sell 25,000 boards during the first year.
   ``They give you the same graphics performance as our Personal
Iris product line (of workstations),'' said company spokeswoman
<PERSON>Jill Grossman</PERSON> of computers that range from <MONEY>$10,000</MONEY> to about
<MONEY>$25,000</MONEY>.
   The boards allow personal computer users to put together a
system to do sophisticated graphics for as little as <MONEY>$7,000</MONEY>,
<PERSON>McCracken</PERSON> said. They should cut into Sun's strategy of offering
workstations ranging from <MONEY>$5,000</MONEY> to <MONEY>$9,000</MONEY>, he said.
   But a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>, also based in Mountain View, said his
company's computers offer more than sophisticated graphics,
including networking capability and data processing not available
on personal computers.
   <PERSON>Robert Herwick</PERSON>, an analyst with the <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION> brokerage
<ORGANIZATION>Hambrecht &amp; Quist Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, said the development of software for the
new boards would help ensure their success.
   He also said the boards should increase demand for Silicon
Graphics' workstations, since those who like the new technology may
want to move up to the company's low-end workstations.
   Silicon Graphics posted a <MONEY>$32 million</MONEY> profit on sales of <MONEY>$420
million</MONEY> in the <DATE>fiscal year ended June 30</DATE>. It had <MONEY>$11.5</MONEY> in profit on
<MONEY>$264 million</MONEY> in sales in the previous year.
</TEXT>
