<HEAD>Lockheed's Cadam Expands Design Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Lockheed Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Cadam Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, branching out into
new territory, said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> it was making its design software
available on workstations made by <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Apollo
Computer Inc</ORGANIZATION>.
   The step should help <ORGANIZATION>Cadam</ORGANIZATION>'s sales while making it easier for
engineers to work together on designs even if they use different
models of computers, said <PERSON>Eric Keller</PERSON>, senior research analyst at
<ORGANIZATION>Gartner Group</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Stamford</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Conn</LOCATION>.
   Cadam Professional software is for designing objects ranging from
cars to printed circuit boards.
   <ORGANIZATION>Cadam</ORGANIZATION> said a feature called Power Link will make it easy for
designs that are developed on a Sun workstation to be moved to an
Apollo workstation, and vice versa.
   <ORGANIZATION>General Motors Corp.</ORGANIZATION> demanded that exchangeability in <DATE>1987</DATE> when
it authorized <ORGANIZATION>Cadam</ORGANIZATION> as one of its two suppliers of computer-aided
design software, along with <ORGANIZATION>McDonnell Douglas Corp</ORGANIZATION>.
   Eventually other computers, including <ORGANIZATION>International Business
Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s RT-PC, will be included in Power Link, <ORGANIZATION>Cadam</ORGANIZATION> said.
The RT-PC was the first workstation to run <ORGANIZATION>Cadam Professional</ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Cadam</ORGANIZATION>
also makes design software that runs on mainframes and personal
computers.
</TEXT>
