<HL> Apollo Cuts Prices
On Workstations,
Matching Its Rivals
---
By William S. Bulkeley
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 06/30/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> APCI
COMPUTERS (EDP) </IN>
<DATELINE> BOSTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Apollo Computer Inc.</ORGANIZATION> slashed prices on its cheapest computer workstations and introduced a new mid-range model that it said is priced lower than competing machines of similar speed. 

   The move, announced here, matches recent price cuts by <LOCATION>Chelmsford</LOCATION>, Mass.-based Apollo's rivals. 
There has been a dogfight in the workstation field lately, with Apollo, <ORGANIZATION>Sun Microsystems Inc.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Mountain View</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>Digital Equipment Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Maynard</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION>, leapfrogging each other with lower prices and new technology. 
Workstations are powerful personal computers used by engineers and other professionals for design and financial modeling tasks. 

   Apollo "is the winner for this week," said <PERSON>John Logan</PERSON>, an analyst with Boston-based <ORGANIZATION>Yankee Group</ORGANIZATION>, a market research firm. 
However, many analysts said they are worried that lowered prices for Apollo's best-selling Domain Series 3000 will hurt its profit margins. 

   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, Apollo shares closed at <MONEY>$20.75</MONEY>, up <MONEY>25 cents</MONEY>. 

   Apollo cut the price on the Domain Series 3000 with a 19-inch monochrome screen <PERCENT>50%</PERCENT> to <MONEY>$5,990</MONEY> from <MONEY>$11,900</MONEY>. 
It said it will introduce a <MONEY>$4,990</MONEY> Domain 3000 with a 15-inch screen in <DATE>December</DATE>. 

   The cuts make Apollo's low-end systems competitive with those from Sun, which started the latest round of price cuts in <DATE>March</DATE>, and <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION>, which cut prices two weeks ago. 
<PERSON>Thomas A. Vanderslice</PERSON>, chairman and president of Apollo, said the price actions weren't prompted by the competitors moves, but instead reflected a longtime plan to cut costs by redesigning the systems. 
He said the action "won't have any impact on profitability." 

   <PERSON>Edward Zander</PERSON>, vice president, marketing, said that <PERSON>Apollo</PERSON> didn't loose ground in the low end of the market after the Sun cuts, but said "there were 90 days when we had to explain to customers why" Sun prices were so much lower. 
Apollo said it had warned customers who resell Apollo computers to reduce their inventories in preparation for a price cut. 

   Apollo's new mid-range workstation, the Domain Series 4000, has a base price of <MONEY>$13,900</MONEY> for a monochrome model without a disk drive. 
Apollo said it can handle four million instructions per second or <ORGANIZATION>MIPS</ORGANIZATION>, a common measure of computer speed. 
It will be available in <DATE>August</DATE>. 

   <PERSON>Marc G. Schulman</PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION>Salomon Brothers Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON>Apollo</PERSON> had "better hope the <DATE>3000</DATE> backlog migrates to the <DATE>4000</DATE>," or revenue will drop sharply because of the price cuts on the <DATE>3000</DATE>. 
<PERSON>Mr. Vanderslice</PERSON> said that Apollo expects about <PERCENT>30%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>40%</PERCENT> of the companies that had planned to buy the <DATE>3000</DATE> will buy the more powerful 4000 instead. 

   Apollo said a <DATE>4000</DATE> machine configured to match archrival Sun's 3/260 model would cost <MONEY>$17,900</MONEY>, compared with <MONEY>$33,900</MONEY> for the Sun workstation. 
However, <PERSON>John Hime</PERSON>, a product marketing manager at <ORGANIZATION>Sun</ORGANIZATION>, said the Apollo comparison is misleading. 
He said the Apollo 4000 would slow down when it had to move information from its central processor to the monitor or to disk memory. 
"It looks like a very unbalanced system," he said. 

   Analysts said they don't expect further price cuts at the low end among workstation makers unless increasingly powerful personal computers start cutting into their core engineering markets. 
<ORGANIZATION>International Business Machines Corp.</ORGANIZATION>'s new PS/2 personal computers, for example, are potential competitors in the workstation market. 
Workstations are more powerful, display sharper pictures and are easier to link together in networks than most personal computers. 
However, companies are likely to continue adding features. 

   Next week Sun is expected to introduce a very powerful workstation that runs at 10 <ORGANIZATION>MIPS</ORGANIZATION> using a reduced instruction set or RISC architecture, a design that enables greater speed. 
Later this year <ORGANIZATION>Digital</ORGANIZATION> is expected to introduce a more powerful version of its VAX-station computer that runs at more than three <ORGANIZATION>MIPS</ORGANIZATION>. 
And Apollo insiders are starting to drop hints about a desktop workstation to be introduced next year that runs in the 25 <ORGANIZATION>MIPS</ORGANIZATION> range. 

